{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17503313","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17503313"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:58:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:58:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2007"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2007","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2007"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.45,0.01,0.16,0.21]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2007"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111693"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2007","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2007"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2007"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93766"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1012"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1598"},{"type":"tags","id":"2173"},{"type":"tags","id":"3800"},{"type":"tags","id":"4069"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4815"},{"type":"tags","id":"4923"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4991"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11622"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12908"},{"type":"tags","id":"12911"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"774"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10793"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11889"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13117"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15330"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15599"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41910"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42431"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44351"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45422"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111693","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111693"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a 10-day history of fever, chills and night sweats, as well as malaise and anorexia. His condition has worsened over the past week. He has a medical history of type 2 diabetes, hypercholesterolaemia and a pre-existing grade 2 systolic murmur. His regular medications include metformin and atorvastatin. He has a five pack-year history of smoking, drinks alcohol socially and uses intravenous substances recreationally.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 121/min, blood pressure 102/66 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 38.8\u00b0C. Injection marks are observed at the left cubital fossa, and tender subcutaneous nodules are palpated at the distal phalanges. On auscultation, a grade 3 pan-systolic murmur is heard at the cardiac apex, along with diffuse crackles in both lungs. Blood cultures taken two days ago have returned positive for \u003Cem\u003ECoxiella burnetii\u003C/em\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following most supports a diagnosis of infective endocarditis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Recreational substance use","Blood culture results","Temperature of 38.8\u00b0C","Tender subcutaneous nodules","Change in cardiac murmur"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EInfective endocarditis (IE) may present either as an acute, rapidly progressive infection or as a subacute or chronic disease characterised by low-grade fever and nonspecific symptoms. Fever, observed in up to 90% of patients, stands as the most common symptom, often accompanied by chills, anorexia, and weight loss. A new or changing cardiac murmur is present in approximately 85% of cases. The 2023 Duke-ISCVID criteria provide updated major and minor clinical criteria for the diagnosis of infective endocarditis. Definite IE is diagnosed by one of these:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Col\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Epathologic criteria: either microbiologic or histopathologic criteria\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eclinical criteria: when two major criteria, one major and three minor criteria, or five minor criteria are met.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ol\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlood culture results\u003C/strong\u003E meet the major microbiological criteria for IE. Under the 2023 Duke-ISCVID criteria, evidence of \u003Cem\u003ECoxiella burnetii\u003C/em\u003E infection demonstrated by positive blood culture, positive PCR or other nucleic acid-based technique from blood, or \u003Cem\u003ECoxiella burnetii\u003C/em\u003E antiphase I IgG antibody titre \u22651:800 constitutes a major criterion. \u003Cem\u003ECoxiella burnetii\u003C/em\u003E is the causative agent of Q fever and can lead to chronic infection including endocarditis, which typically affects patients with pre-existing valvular disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERecreational substance use\u003C/strong\u003E is recognised as a predisposing condition in the minor criteria. The 2023 revision specifically includes injection drug use as a predisposition, acknowledging its importance as a risk factor for IE.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETemperature of 38.8\u00b0C\u003C/strong\u003E meets the minor criterion of fever, defined as temperature \u226538.0\u00b0C. While fever is common in IE, it alone is insufficient for diagnosis and represents only a minor criterion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETender subcutaneous nodules\u003C/strong\u003E at the distal phalanges represent Osler nodes, which are painful, raised lesions on the fingers or toes. These are classified under immunological phenomena in the minor criteria, along with glomerulonephritis, positive rheumatoid factor, and Roth spots.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChange in cardiac murmur\u003C/strong\u003E from grade 2 to grade 3 represents a worsening of a pre-existing murmur. Under the 2023 criteria, this constitutes a minor criterion. Only new valvular regurgitation (not simply a change in pre-existing murmur) would meet major criteria when demonstrated by physical examination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["According to the 2023 Duke-ISCVID criteria, definite infective endocarditis is diagnosed if pathologic or clinical criteria are met.","The clinical criteria for diagnosis require two major criteria, one major and three minor criteria, or five minor criteria.","Major microbiological criteria include two separate positive blood cultures for typical organisms or evidence of Coxiella burnetii infection with antiphase I IgG antibody titre \u22651:800."],"references":["Fowler Jr VG, Durack DT, Selton-Suty C, Athan E, Bayer AS, Chamis AL, et al. The 2023 Duke-International Society for Cardiovascular Infectious Diseases criteria for infective endocarditis: updating the modified Duke criteria. Clinical Infectious Diseases. 2023 Aug 15;77(4):518-26. Available at: https://academic.oup.com/cid/article/77/4/518/7151107"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93766"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2007"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93766","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93766"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-18T18:51:20+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08